Success StoriesClaudia Pavlovich

Claudia Pavlovich

Claudia Pavlovich

Success Story

Reaching and influencing Mexican voters

The Sonoran gubernatorial candidate rode targeted video ad campaigns to a decisive win, reaching a wide and diverse audience of 1.1 million people and jumping 24 points in the polls in just 3 months.
  • 1.1 million Sonorans reached
  • 71,000 more votes than closest opponent
  • 24-point turnaround (7-point victory after starting with a 17-point deficit)

Their Story

A hometown heroine

Claudia Pavlovich is the first female governor of Sonora, Mexico. A native of the state, Pavlovich took office in September 2015 following a landslide victory.

Their Goal

Making introductions

The campaign team needed to build name recognition for Pavlovich among Sonoran voters and help people get to know her and her platform. The aim was to overcome a very large electoral deficit to win.
The use of Facebook in the Sonora campaign was a turning point in Mexican politics. Our party is quickly adapting to this new era of digital communication as an opportunity to engage young and non-involved citizens.
Manlio Fabio Beltrones, President of the Institutional Revolutionary Party

Their Solution

On-target messaging

To counter the expense and limitations of TV advertising under Mexico’s strict election laws, the Pavlovich team worked with agencies Digital State and Upstream Communications to design a Facebook campaign that would effectively highlight Claudia’s strengths and how she differed from her opponents.

Showcasing a winning personality

Digital State produced 34 video ads that featured Claudia Pavlovich speaking directly and frankly to her audience to demonstrate her clear vision and understanding of the state’s needs. Each ad included a caption summarizing a key policy point, as well as campaign slogans such as #otrosonoraya—“A new Sonora now.”
Read More

Moving fast and testing creative

Launching these ads on Facebook meant that Upstream Communications and Digital State were able to quickly and efficiently test different video creative and capitalize on trending discussions—something that wouldn’t have been possible on Mexican TV. Combining ad optimization with Facebook video and ad insights gave the team the key statistics it needed to improve messaging throughout the campaign.
Facebook’s ability to target distinctive voter segments also allowed the Pavlovich team to reach a wide and diverse audience with individually relevant content at a much lower cost than TV—and without the stringent restrictions.

Products used

  • Page Publishing
  • Ads
  • Video
  • Desktop News Feed
  • Core Targeting
  • Conversion Tracking
  • Custom Audiences

Goals

  • Raise Brand Awareness

Their Success

Overwhelming the odds

Pavlovich’s targeted Facebook campaign showcased the Governor’s strength and integrity and helped her achieve an historic upset, where she received 71,000 more votes than her closest opponent. Between March 1–June 1, 2015, the campaign achieved:
  • 1.1 million Sonorans reached, with 3.2 million post engagements at a cost of $.01 per engagement
  • 71,000 more votes than main opponent
  • 24-point turnaround (7-point victory after starting with a 17-point deficit)
As applied mathematics and physics revolutionized the world and human interactions, Facebook has also done for political communications. Facebook video ads allowed us to tell Governor Pavlovich’s story and reach our audience in a way no other medium could. We could not have overcome a 17-point deficit to achieve a 7-point victory without the platform: it was an integral part of her victory.
Hugo Scherer, Campaign Manager, Kevin Hickson, Vice President, Upstream Communications, and Jorge Audiffred, CEO, Digital State
